Absolutely! Let’s summarize a clean, step-by-step plan to install Zabbix 7.4.6 on Debian 13 (Trixie). I’ll make it concise but complete, including server, agent, frontend, and MariaDB database.

Step 1: Update the system
sudo apt update
sudo apt upgrade -y
sudo apt install wget curl gnupg lsb-release -y

Step 2: Add Zabbix 7.4 repository

Download and install the correct repo package:

wget https://repo.zabbix.com/zabbix/7.4/release/debian/pool/main/z/zabbix-release/zabbix-release_latest_7.4+debian13_all.deb
sudo dpkg -i zabbix-release_latest_7.4+debian13_all.deb
sudo apt update

Step 3: Install Zabbix packages
sudo apt install zabbix-server-mysql zabbix-frontend-php zabbix-sql-scripts zabbix-agent zabbix-apache-conf -y


Use zabbix-nginx-conf instead of zabbix-apache-conf if you prefer nginx.

Step 4: Install and configure MariaDB
sudo apt install mariadb-server -y
sudo systemctl enable --now mariadb
sudo mysql_secure_installation


Create the Zabbix database and user:

CREATE DATABASE zabbix CHARACTER SET utf8mb4 COLLATE utf8mb4_bin;
CREATE USER 'zabbix'@'localhost' IDENTIFIED BY 'zabbix';
GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON zabbix.* TO 'zabbix'@'localhost';
FLUSH PRIVILEGES;
EXIT;

###### ISSUE##### Step 5: Import initial database schema
zcat /usr/share/zabbix-sql-scripts/mysql/create.sql.gz | mysql -u zabbix -p zabbix
Note: Bypass this step and do this
Step 5: 

>>> Stop Zabbix to avoid writes during restore
sudo systemctl stop zabbix-server
>>> (You already did this, but safe to repeat) allow routine creation while binlog is on
mysql -u root -p -e "SET GLOBAL log_bin_trust_function_creators = 1;"
>>> Restore directly as root so DEFINER=`root`@`localhost` is valid
mysql -u root -p zabbix < /var/backups/zabbix_backup_20251103_020808.sql
>>> Turn the trust back off (optional but recommended)
mysql -u root -p -e "SET GLOBAL log_bin_trust_function_creators = 0;"
>>> Start Zabbix and watch logs
sudo systemctl start zabbix-server
sudo tail -n 200 /var/log/zabbix/zabbix_server.log


Step 6: Configure Zabbix server

Edit /etc/zabbix/zabbix_server.conf:

DBHost=localhost
DBName=zabbix
DBUser=zabbix
DBPassword=StrongPasswordHere


Save and exit.

Step 7: Install and configure PHP
sudo apt install php8.2 php8.2-mysql php8.2-gd php8.2-mbstring libapache2-mod-php8.2 -y
sudo a2enmod php8.2
sudo systemctl restart apache2


Set timezone in /etc/php/8.2/apache2/php.ini:

date.timezone = Your/Timezone

Step 8: Start Zabbix services
sudo systemctl enable --now zabbix-server zabbix-agent apache2

Step 9: Complete web setup

Open a browser and go to:

http://YOUR_SERVER_IP/zabbix


Follow the wizard:

Select language

Check prerequisites

Enter DB credentials (zabbix / StrongPasswordHere)

Finish installation

Step 10: Default login

Username: Admin

Password: zabbix

Change the password immediately after login.

✅ After this, you have a fully working Zabbix 7.4.6 server + agent + web frontend on Debian 13.

